Exploring autocorrelation [in time & space]

###Example with temporal autocorrelation (time-series)

Simulate some correlated noise with AR(1)

set.seed(2)
z<-w<-rnorm(100, sd=18)# noise
for (t in 2:100) z[t]<- 0.8 * z[t-1] + w[t]# the AR(1) process

# the z[t] is the AR(1) process; zt = 0.8*zt-1 + wt, with wt = gaussian white noise with var = 20

plot(z, type='l')

Lets simulate a time series using the autocorrelated noise.

Time <- 1:100
x <- 50 + 0.8 * Time + z # simulate time-series with autocor and noise and positive trend
plot(x, xlab="time", type="l")

There is apparent trend. Let’s examine it. Fit a linear model to the data (ignoring autocorrelation)

x.lm<-lm(x~Time)
summary(x.lm) # estimate of slope = 0.38
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = x ~ Time)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -70.013 -18.180   0.558  18.119  64.486 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 69.27189    5.52556  12.537  < 2e-16 ***
## Time         0.38499    0.09499   4.053 0.000101 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 27.42 on 98 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1435, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1348 
## F-statistic: 16.43 on 1 and 98 DF,  p-value: 0.0001015
# sd error of estimates: intercept=5.5 and slope=0.09

Linear regression assumes independence of observations and residuals. Let’s check if this holds here.

acf(resid(x.lm))

Let see the partial residual plot

pacf(resid(x.lm)) # partial acf shows lag-1 autocorrelation (as expected)

this means that our estimation of the coefficients for timeseries trends can be wrong

Fitting a generalised least-square model, taking AR into account. What happens to the standard errors of the estimated parameters? The temporal trend is now bordeline significant and the SD of parameters larger

#library(nlme)
x.gls <- gls(x~Time, cor=corAR1(0.7)) # fitting autocorrelation of order 1 (Here using cor=0.7 because we knew already)
summary(x.gls)
## Generalized least squares fit by REML
##   Model: x ~ Time 
##   Data: NULL 
##        AIC      BIC    logLik
##   890.3855 900.7254 -441.1928
## 
## Correlation Structure: AR(1)
##  Formula: ~1 
##  Parameter estimate(s):
##       Phi 
## 0.6975682 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                Value Std.Error  t-value p-value
## (Intercept) 66.44187 12.931722 5.137898  0.0000
## Time         0.42370  0.219782 1.927822  0.0568
## 
##  Correlation: 
##      (Intr)
## Time -0.858
## 
## Standardized residuals:
##           Min            Q1           Med            Q3           Max 
## -2.4030369405 -0.6186876673  0.0006914511  0.6725653520  2.3171444898 
## 
## Residual standard error: 28.65019 
## Degrees of freedom: 100 total; 98 residual
# the st errors of parameters is much larger now: intercept=12.9, slope= 0.21

Which is the “best” model? Ask AIC

AIC(x.lm)
## [1] 950.0281
AIC(x.gls)# better suppored model based on AIC
## [1] 890.3855

Plot both model prediction. Trends are only marginally different, but the confidence intervals are larger whan accounting for temporal autocorrelation. Hence the trends become non-significant at alpha=0.05

plot(x, xlab="time", type="l")
abline(a=coef(x.lm)[1],b=coef(x.lm)[2], col='blue' )
abline(a=coef(x.gls)[1],b=coef(x.gls)[2], col='red' )

SPatial Autocorrelation

####Spatial structure is more complex than temporal; there are two dimensions

Let’s simulate some sparse coordinates [with no real meaning!]

Long.x=seq(from=100, to=120, 0.2)+rnorm(101, 0, 4)
Lat.y=seq(20,40, 0.2)+rnorm(101, 0, 4)

#plot(Long.x, Lat.y)

Simulate some spatially structured variable (e.g. bird diversity) using the ncf::rmvr.spa function Then simulate some environmental variable correlated with latitude

install.packages('ncf')
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/6z/h_qqs24j389gqllrq766mvl80000gn/T//RtmpMqTZzS/downloaded_packages
library(ncf)
div.ncf=rmvn.spa(Long.x, Lat.y, 20, method = "exp", nugget = 1)# we call it div.nfc

div.ncf=div.ncf-min(div.ncf) # dirty trick to include only positive values


env.var=1+2*Lat.y -0.05*(Long.x)+rnorm(101,0,4)# environmental variable reflecting lat and long

plot(Lat.y,env.var) # exagerated trend of environmental variable with latitude

Plot the relation between div.nfc and env.var; looks positive

plot(div.ncf~env.var)

Put the data together, coordinates, environmental variable and diversity.

bird.diversity=data.frame(Lat.y=Lat.y, Long.x=Long.x, Bird_div=div.ncf, Env.var=env.var)

Specify what are the coordinates, for plotting variograms.

coordinates(bird.diversity)=~Long.x+Lat.y

Lets have a look at the variogram. Looks pretty strong autocorrelation pattern.

plot(gstat::variogram(Bird_div~ Long.x+Lat.y , bird.diversity))

Fit a simple model with no spatial correlation.

model1 <- gls(log(Bird_div + 1) ~ log(env.var + 1) , data = bird.diversity )
summary(model1)

Check the residual variogram from the model. Some clear pattern of correlated observation at short distances.

plot(nlme::Variogram(model1, form = ~Long.x + Lat.y, resType = "normalized"), ylim=c(0,1.5))

# nearby locations show rather low variation. A clear patter of spatial autocorrelation

Now, lets fit a gls model including Gaussian autocorrelation function

model.sp.gauss<-gls( log(Bird_div + 1) ~ log(Env.var + 1) , correlation = corGaus(form = ~Long.x + Lat.y, nugget=T), data = bird.diversity )
summary(model.sp.gauss)

And the check the residual variogram of this spatially explicit model. The patterns are different, and no real trend with distance is evident.

plot(nlme::Variogram(model.sp.gauss, form = ~Long.x + Lat.y, resType = "normalized"))

Which model is favored according to AIC. Clear support for model2 (lower AIC).

AIC(model1, model.sp.gauss)
##                df       AIC
## model1          3  38.23573
## model.sp.gauss  5 -84.47821

We can visually compare the fits of the two model. Most of the apparent effect of environmental variable on bird diversity seems to come from an autocorrelation process

plot(log(Bird_div+1)~log(Env.var+1), bird.diversity)
abline(a=coef(model1)[1], b=coef(model1)[2]) # add fit from model1 (w/o spatial autocor)
abline(a=coef(model.sp.gauss)[1], b=coef(model.sp.gauss)[2], col="blue") #add the model fit from the gaussian autocor model
